Solution:
Let $P$ be the point $(-3,-1)$, and let $P'$ be its image after the reflection.  Let $Q$ be the point $(5,3)$.

[asy]
unitsize(0.5 cm);

pair P, Pp, Q, refl;

P = (-3,-1);
Q = (5,3);
refl = (1,1);
Pp = 2*foot(P, refl, refl + (1,0)) - P;

draw((-8,0)--(8,0));
draw((0,-4)--(0,4));
draw(P--Q);
draw(P--Pp,Arrow(6));
draw(Pp--Q,Arrow(6));
draw(refl + (-8,0)--refl + (8,0),dashed);

label("$P$", P, S);
label("$P'$", Pp, N);
label("$Q$", Q, N);
label("$y = mx + b$", refl + (-3,-1), E);
[/asy]

Let $Q'$ be the reflection of $Q$ across the line $y = mx + b.$  Then $Q'$ lies on line $PQ,$ and $PQ'$ is perpendicular to $y = mx + b.$

[asy]
