The volume of the sphere of radius $r + 1$ is $\frac{4}{3} \pi (r + 1)^3,$ and the volume of the sphere of radius 1 is $\frac{4}{3} \pi.$  The ratio of these volumes is
\[\frac{\frac{4}{3} \pi (r + 1)^3}{\frac{4}{3} \pi} = (r + 1)^3.\]Thus, if $P$ lies inside one of the small spheres, then $P$ must lie inside one of the spheres of radius $r + 1,$ centered at $O.$  The probability that $P$ lies inside one of these spheres is
\[\frac{\text{volume of the union of the spheres of radius } r + 1}{\text{volume of the circumscribed sphere}}.\]This probability is a function of $r.$

